'You''ll need an AJAX Callback process. This one is called DEPT_JSON<br>',
'This is the process that returns options back to the dropdown after the user types. ',
'Be as creative as you need here, any SQL technique could be used.<br>',
'For code alternatives see <a href="http://rimblas.com/blog/2015/01/12c-with-inline-plsql-json_from_sql-bind-variables-and-ajax/" target="_blank">12c WITH inline PL/SQL, json_from_sql, Bind Variables and AJAX</a>',
'<code>',
'  -- Aliased values as "id" and "text" to support what select2 expects  ',
'  apex_util.json_from_sql(''with function param return varchar2 is begin return apex_application.g_x01; end;''  ',
'                      || '' select deptno "id", dname "text" ''  ',
'                      || ''  from dept''  ',
'                      || '' where (instr (upper(dname), upper(param())) > 0)''  ',
'                      || '' order by dname''  ',
'                      );  ',
'</code>',
'<hr>',
'',
'<br>',
'There''s an After Refresh Dynamic Action, that fires on Page Load, on this page that will perform the following steps:',
'<code>',
'// 1. Define the options for the Select2 element. including the .ajax for Lazy Loading',
'var deptOptions = {',
'dropdownAutoWidth: true, ',
'minimumInputLength: 1,',
'ajax: { // instead of writing the function to execute the request we use Select2''s convenient helper',
'        url: ''wwv_flow.show'',',
'        dataType: ''json'',',
'        quietMillis: 500,',
'        data: function (term, page) {',
'            return {',
'                p_request      : ''APPLICATION_PROCESS=DEPT_JSON'',',
'                p_flow_id      : $v(''pFlowId''),',
'                p_flow_step_id : $v(''pFlowStepId''),',
'                p_instance     : $v(''pInstance''),',
'                x01            : term',
'            };',
'        },',
'        results: function (data, page) { ',
'            return { results: data.row };',
'        },',
'        cache: true ',
'    }, // end ajax call',
'initSelection: function(element, callback) {',
'        var id = element.val();',
'        if (id) {',
'            var data = {id: element.val(), text: deptDic[id]};',
'            // dcDic is a JS array with all the values needed to pre-polulate the page',
'            // if only to rows on the tab form have values then dcDic has two entries.',
'            // Optionall, add another ajax callback here to grab the text for the ID,',
'            // However, I don''t like the performance hit here with a lot of rows',
'            callback(data);',
'        }',
'    }, // end init selection',
'placeholder: " ", // Allow clear seems to only work with remote data if there is a placeholder',
'allowClear: true};',
'',
'// 2. Change desired items to select2 (The select2 code is added by the "Manual Select2" Plugin)',
'$(''.empDeptno'').select2(deptOptions);</code>',
'<hr>',
'',
'',
'<br>',
'The deptDic element, referenced in the DA above, is useful (required) on first load to populate the initial values. It''s possible to load the initial values with AJAX calls, but if the volume is large this would take a long time. Thus pre-populating '
||'them into deptDict optimizes the process.<br>',
'A Dynamic PL/SQL Region handles this.',
'',
'<code>',
'-- Code for populating deptDic',
'-- place this as a PL/SQL Dynamic Content region BEFORE your tabular form region',
'declare',
' l_need_comma boolean := false;',
'begin',
'  -- Create "dictionary" arrays: ',
'  --   deptDic for Departments',
'  -- They are used for the populating the Select2 items',
'  -- that already have codes and avoid an extra AJAX call for each one.',
'  sys.htp.p(''&lt;script>'');',
'',
'  sys.htp.prn(''var deptDic={'');',
'  ',
'  for d in (',
'    select d.dname  as description,',
'           d.deptno as code',
'      from emp e',
'         , dept d',
'     where e.deptno = d.deptno',
'     order by 1    ',
'  )',
'  loop',
'    if l_need_comma then',
'      sys.htp.prn('','');',
'    else',
'      l_need_comma := true;',
'    end if;',
'    sys.htp.prn(d.code || '':"'' || replace(d.description, ''"'',''\"'') || ''"'');',
'  end loop;',
'  sys.htp.p(''};'');',
'',
'  sys.htp.p(''&lt;/script>'');',
'',
'end;',
'</code>',
'<hr>',
'',
'',
'',
'<br><br>',
'View blog post <a target="_blank" href="http://rimblas.com/blog/2016/01/using-select2-on-apex-tabular-forms/">rimblas.com/blog/2016/01/using-select2-on-apex-tabular-forms/</a>'))
,p_plug_query_options=>'DERIVED_REPORT_COLUMNS'
,p_attribute_01=>'N'
,p_attribute_02=>'HTML'
);
